generif.text: Results from a study on gene expression variability markers in early-stage human embryos shows that PPP6R3 is a putative expression variability marker for the 3-day, 8-cell embryo stage.

Molecular analyses revealed the presence and amplification of the novel PPPR6-USP6 gene fusion, which resulted in USP6 mRNA transcriptional upregulation. These findings further support the oncogenic role of the USP6 protease in mesenchymal neoplasia and expand the biologic potential of Nodular fasciitis

we found a DPP9-PPP6R3 fusion transcript in one tumor showing a matching genomic 11;19-translocation. Another tumor had a rearrangement of DPP9 with PLIN3. Both rearrangements were associated with diminished expression of the 3' end of DPP9 corresponding to the breakpoints identified by RNA-seq.

The substitution of Ala in nine putative phosphorylation sites in SAPS3 was required to prevent CK2 activation of the phosphatase. Different CK2 chemical inhibitors equally increased phosphorylation of endogenous AURKA in living cells, consistent with reduction in PP6 activity.

name: protein phosphatase 6 regulatory subunit 3

reactome.name: Transport to the Golgi and subsequent modification

summary: Protein phosphatase regulatory subunits, such as SAPS3, modulate the activity of protein phosphatase catalytic subunits by restricting substrate specificity, recruiting substrates, and determining the intracellular localization of the holoenzyme. SAPS3 is a regulatory subunit for the protein phosphatase-6 catalytic subunit (PPP6C; MIM 612725) (Stefansson and Brautigan, 2006 [PubMed 16769727]).[supplied by OMIM, Nov 2010].
